                            <h1>
                            Be Men!
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p2" class="">Elder Carlos E. Asay</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p3" class="">Of the Presidency of the Seventy</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <img src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/gospel-library/magazine/ensignlp.nfo:o:1fa0.jpg" alt="Elder Carlos E. Asay">
                                        
                                        
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">92905_000_020</span>
			
			<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p4" class="">A young man of deacon age reported: &ldquo;I feel a lot of pressure from my friends to smoke and steal and things like that. &hellip; My best friends are really pushing me to do it. They call me a <span class="emphasis">pansy </span>and a <span class="emphasis">mamma&rsquo;s boy </span>if I don&rsquo;t. I really don&rsquo;t like the idea of smoking but my good friend Steve told me in front of some of my friends, &lsquo;Kevin, you&rsquo;re <span class="emphasis">an idiot </span>and <span class="emphasis">a chicken </span>wrapped up in one little body.&rsquo;&rdquo; (J. Santrock, <span class="emphasis">Adolescence,</span> New York: William C. Brown, 1987; italics added.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p5" class="">An eighteen-year-old priest recounted:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p6" class="">&ldquo;On one occasion, I was persuaded to join a group on a weekend excursion. I was told that the [plans] for the day included &hellip; sightseeing, a lunch, and a movie. I was promised that there would be no [inappropriate activities]. All &hellip; knew that I was a Latter-day Saint and &hellip; deeply committed to the moral standards of the Church.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p7" class="">&ldquo;Upon reaching the city, we visited a place or two of historical significance and ate lunch. Then the inevitable happened&mdash;the group turned toward a bar and a house of [prostitution]. I refused to enter these dens of iniquity, and I openly expressed my anger over the broken promises of my associates.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p8" class="">&ldquo;As I walked away &hellip; my companions taunted me by shouting, &lsquo;When are you going to grow up?&rsquo; &lsquo;When will you stop being a sissy and a religious fanatic?&rsquo; &lsquo;When are you going to be a man?&rsquo;&rdquo; (Carlos E. Asay, <span class="emphasis">In the Lord&rsquo;s Service, </span>Salt Lake City: Deseret Book Co., 1990, p. 46.)</p>
			<div>
				<h2>Who Is a Man?</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p10" class="">It seems that everyone at some time or another is invited by peers to smoke, drink, steal, or engage in other immoral acts, all under the pretense of manhood. And when someone refuses to participate, he is often ridiculed and called names like pansy, mamma&rsquo;s boy, idiot, chicken, sissy, and religious fanatic. Such names are used by peers who equate manliness with the ability to drink liquor, blow tobacco smoke out of all the facial cavities, sow one&rsquo;s wild oats like some animal on the street, and break moral laws without a twinge of conscience.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p11" class="">We see colorful advertisements on billboards, in magazines, and on the television screen promoting cigarettes, beer, and other vices. Those who use cunning tactics to peddle their wares disregard the souls of young people and love only their money. They would have us believe that a person with a cigarette or alcoholic beverage in hand is a man, when in reality he is nothing more than a slave to a destructive substance. They would have us believe that a person who engages in illicit sex is a man, when in reality he is nothing more than an abuser of those who are &ldquo;tender,&rdquo; and &ldquo;chaste,&rdquo; and &ldquo;delicate.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/2.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 2:7</a>.) They would have us believe that brute force, or crude behavior, uncontrolled temper, foul language, and dirty appearance make a man, when in reality these characteristics are animalistic at best and the opposite of manhood at worst.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p12" class="">We who bear the priesthood, must be on guard; we must not be influenced by barbarian voices in our quest to become men. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/14.8-11?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 14:8&ndash;11</a>.) We must remember that &ldquo;God created man in his own image&rdquo; and that man is expected to keep that image engraven upon his countenance. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/gen/1.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Gen. 1:27</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.14,19?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:14, 19</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p13" class="">&ldquo;What is man?&rdquo; asked the psalmist. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ps/8.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ps. 8:4</a>.) The answer: &ldquo;[God] made him a little lower than the angels, and hast crowned him with glory and honour.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ps/8.4-6?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ps. 8:4&ndash;6</a>.) It is, therefore, our responsibility to climb ever upward and to wear God-given crowns honorably. Young men, especially those of a &ldquo;chosen generation&rdquo; and &ldquo;royal priesthood,&rdquo; must understand that they are the spiritual offspring of God and that no one becomes in truth a man until he reverences the Father of spirits and allows inner powers to control his thoughts, words, and actions. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-pet/2.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Pet. 2:9</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/17.28?lang=eng#27" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 17:28</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/heb/12.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Heb. 12:9</a>.)</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>What Makes a Man a Man?</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p15" class="">What makes a man a man? This is a question used in a popular beer ad. The suggestion of that advertisement is that by drinking the beer the consumer becomes a man. How devious and how very stupid! Those who try to get you to drink alcoholic beverages and use drugs have total disregard for you, you who are the &ldquo;temples of God.&rdquo; Hence, they would have you defile your body and offend the Spirit of God that dwells within you. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/3.16-17?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 3:16&ndash;17</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p16" class="">What makes a man a man? Let&rsquo;s turn to the Book of Mormon and Father Lehi for an answer. A short time before his death, Lehi gave this charge to his sons: &ldquo;Arise from the dust, &hellip; and <span class="emphasis">be men.</span>&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/1.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 1:21</a>; italics added.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p17" class="">&ldquo;Awake from a deep sleep, yea, even from the sleep of hell, and shake off the awful chains by which ye are bound.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/1.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 1:13</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p18" class="">&ldquo;Be determined in one mind and in one heart, united in all things.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/1.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 1:21</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p19" class="">&ldquo;Put on the armor of righteousness. &hellip; Come forth out of obscurity. &hellip; Rebel no more.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/1.23-24?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 1:23&ndash;24</a>.)</p>
				<ul class="bullet">
					<li><span class="label">&bull;</span>
						
						<p>The challenge to <span class="emphasis">&ldquo;arise from the dust&rdquo; </span>means to overcome evil behaviors that destroy character and ruin lives. Physical appetites must be controlled.</p>
					</li>
					<li><span class="label">&bull;</span>
						
						<p><span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Awake from a deep sleep, &hellip; </span>even from the sleep of hell&rdquo; suggests a process of learning and becoming aware of God&rsquo;s holy purposes. No sleep is deeper or more deadly than the sleep of ignorance.</p>
					</li>
					<li><span class="label">&bull;</span>
						
						<p><span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Shake off the awful chains by which ye are bound&rdquo; </span>indicates the need to overcome bad habits, even the seemingly little habits that grow into strong &ldquo;chains of hell.&rdquo; (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/26.22?lang=eng#21" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 26:22</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:7</a>.)</p>
					</li>
					<li><span class="label">&bull;</span>
						
						<p><span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Be determined in one mind and in one heart, united in all things&rdquo; </span>requires full commitment to righteousness and a singleness of purpose so that one&rsquo;s will is made compatible with the will of God.</p>
					</li>
					<li><span class="label">&bull;</span>
						
						<p><span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Put on the armor of righteousness&rdquo; </span>reminds us of the need to wear the helmet of salvation, pick up the sword of truth, use the shield of faith, and accept the full protective coverings of the Lord. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/eph/6.11-18?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Eph. 6:11&ndash;18</a>.)</p>
					</li>
					<li><span class="label">&bull;</span>
						
						<p><span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Come forth out of obscurity&rdquo; </span>instructs one to model goodness and serve as a light to others. True men are living light fountains which are pleasant to be near. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/103.9-10?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 103:9&ndash;10</a>.)</p>
					</li>
					<li><span class="label">&bull;</span>
						
						<p><span class="emphasis">&ldquo;Rebel no more&rdquo; </span>makes it perfectly clear that ignoring or willfully breaking commandments is a wasteful effort.</p>
					</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Vicious Lie</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p28" class="">There is a lie&mdash;a vicious lie&mdash;circulating among the Latter-day Saints and taking its toll among the young. And it is that a &ldquo;balanced man&rdquo; is one who deliberately guards against becoming too righteous. This lie would have you believe that it is possible to live successfully and happily as a &ldquo;double-minded man&rdquo; with one foot in Babylon and one foot in Zion. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/james/1.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">James 1:8</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p29" class="">I love this story of two young men who had been schooled in a monastery. One morning as they sought adventure, they passed a cathedral. The more righteous of the two remembered that they had not prayed that morning and said, &ldquo;How can [we] hope for [God&rsquo;s] blessing upon the day?&rdquo;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p30" class="">The less righteous one responded: &ldquo;My friend, I have prayed so much during the last two months &hellip; that I feel that I have [somewhat] over-prayed myself.&rdquo;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p31" class="">&ldquo;How can a man have too much religion?&rdquo; asked the first. &ldquo;It is the one thing that availeth. A man is but a beast as he lives from day to day, eating and drinking, breathing and sleeping. <span class="emphasis">It is only when he raises himself, and concerns himself with the immortal spirit within him, that he becomes in [very] truth a man. </span>Bethink ye how sad a thing it would be that the blood of the Redeemer should be spilled to no purpose.&rdquo; (A. Conan Doyle, &ldquo;The White Company,&rdquo; in <span class="emphasis">Works of A. Conan Doyle, </span>New York: Cosmopolitan Book Corporation, 1988, pp. 58&ndash;59; italics added.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p32" class="">Can a man be too righteous? Too Christlike? Impossible! Can the so-called &ldquo;balanced man&rdquo; walk successfully the beam between good and evil? No. Each step is shaky, and eventually he will teeter and fall and break himself against the commandments of God.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p33" class="">Fleshliness never was manliness, and it never will be. A real man is one who yields to the enticings of the Holy Spirit and seeks to acquire Christlike virtues. A real man is one who allows the Spirit to direct the course and to call the cadence in his life. &ldquo;Remember, to be carnally-minded is death, and to be spiritually-minded is life eternal.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/9.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 9:39</a>.)</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h2>Examples of Manliness</h2>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p35" class="">A man of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a> stood on October 1, 1959, before a crowd of 1,500 people in a church within the shadow of the Kremlin and boldly referred to Jesus as the great Redeemer. He said in an emotion-filled voice:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p36" class="">&ldquo;I believe very firmly in prayer. It is possible to reach out and tap that unseen power which gives us such strength and such anchor in time of need. &hellip; Be not afraid. Keep His commandments. Love one another. Love all mankind. Strive for peace and all will be well. Truth will endure. Time is on the side of truth.&rdquo; (Ezra Taft Benson, <span class="emphasis">Cross Fire: The Eight Years with Eisenhower, </span>Garden City, N.Y.: Doubleday and Co., 1962, pp. 485&ndash;88.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p37" class="">People wept openly on that occasion, including newsmen who had reluctantly attended the worship service. One newsman, a former marine, ranked the experience as one of the two most spiritual and memorable of his life.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p38" class="">There was a man in that cathedral in Russia on that special day. His name, Ezra Taft Benson&mdash;he who now presides as the President, prophet of the Church.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p39" class="">Parley P. Pratt provides us with a description of a real man in his account of his imprisonment in Richmond, Missouri, with <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a> and others. On one of those awful nights in jail, Brother Pratt and his associates were exposed to the filthy language of their guards as they bragged of their deeds of rape, murder, robbery, and other crimes committed against <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/">the Mormons</a>. When the Prophet Joseph could bear it no more, he rose to his feet and spoke with a voice of thunder:</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p40" class="">&ldquo;SILENCE, ye fiends of the infernal pit. In the name of <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a> I rebuke you, and command you to be still; I will not live another minute and bear such language. Cease such talk, or you or I die THIS INSTANT!&rdquo;</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p41" class="">Said Elder Pratt: &ldquo;I have seen the ministers of justice, clothed in magisterial robes &hellip; in the Courts of England; I have witnessed a Congress in solemn session&nbsp;&hellip;&nbsp;; I have tried to conceive of kings&nbsp;&hellip;&nbsp;; and of emperors assembled to decide the fate of kingdoms; but dignity and majesty have I seen but <span class="emphasis">once, </span>as it stood in chains, at midnight, in a dungeon in an obscure village of Missouri.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Autobiography of Parley P. Pratt, </span>Salt Lake City: Deseret Book Co., 1985, pp. 179&ndash;80.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p42" class="">There was a man! Joseph Smith, the prophet of the Restoration.</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p43" class="">The Savior, the perfect model of manliness, stood before his tormentors having been scourged, beaten, spat upon, and platted with a crown of thorns. Pilate admitted, &ldquo;I find no fault in him.&rdquo; Then he pronounced those irrefutable and piercing words: &ldquo;Behold the man!&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/19.4-5?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 19:4&ndash;5</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p44" class="">Jesus, our Savior, was <span class="emphasis">the </span>man among men, for he &ldquo;increased in wisdom and stature, and in favour with God and man&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/2.52?lang=eng#51" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 2:52</a>); he subjected the flesh to the Spirit and yielded not to temptation (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/15.1-8?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 15:1&ndash;8</a>); he learned obedience by the things which he suffered (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/heb/5.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Heb. 5:8</a>); he grew from grace to grace (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/93.12-14?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 93:12&ndash;14</a>); and, in the words of Shakespeare:</p>
				<div class="figure">
					<div class="stanza" id="">
						<div class="line" id=""><span class="emphasis">His life was gentle, and the elements</span></div>
						<div class="line" id=""><span class="emphasis">So mix&rsquo;d in him that Nature might stand up</span></div>
						<div class="line" id=""><span class="emphasis">And say to all the world &ldquo;This was a man!&rdquo;</span></div>
					</div>
					<div class="citationInfo" id="">
						<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p48" class="">(<span class="emphasis">Julius Caesar, </span>as cited in David O. McKay, <span class="emphasis">Gospel Ideals, </span>Salt Lake City: Improvement Era, 1953, p. 353.)</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p49" class="">Thus, he, the only sinless and perfect man who ever walked this earth, is qualified to state: &ldquo;What manner of men ought ye to be? Verily I say unto you, even as I am.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:27</a>.)</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p50" class="">King David instructed his son Solomon, &ldquo;Be thou strong &hellip; and shew thyself <span class="emphasis">a man;</span></p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1992/05/be-men.p51" class="">&ldquo;And keep the charge of the Lord thy God, to walk in his ways, to keep his statutes, and his commandments, &hellip; that thou mayest prosper in all that thou doest.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/1-kgs/2.2-3?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Kgs. 2:2&ndash;3</a>; italics added.) I echo this charge&mdash;Be men! Be men of Christ! [See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/3.29?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 3:29</a>.]  Be men of God! For this I pray, in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
			</div>
		
                            
                            
                            
